  "prompt": "What happens when a batsman hit a shot and ball hits the spidercam?",
  "response": "In cricket, if a batsman hits a shot and the ball hits the Spidercam (a suspended camera system used for broadcasting), the following rules typically apply:\n\n1. Dead Ball: When the ball touches the Spidercam, it is considered a dead ball. This means the ball is no longer in play.\n\n2. Replay: The ball is called dead, and the umpires will signal a dead ball.\n\n3. Replay of the Ball: The delivery will be re-bowled without any runs being scored or any dismissal taking effect.\n\n4. No Runs: No runs will be added to the batting team's score for that particular delivery.\n\n5. No Dismissal: If the ball hits the Spidercam, it cannot result in a dismissal, even if the ball would have otherwise been caught or led to a run-out.\n\nThis rule ensures fairness and prevents any unintended interference with the game due to broadcasting equipment. The primary goal is to ensure that the ball's path is not artificially altered by external objects.\n\nThe exact implementation might vary slightly depending on the specific cricket governing body and the match's playing conditions, but the general principle remains the same.",
